# Day 8 - Data Backup for Developer

## Task
Create a compressed archive of the `/data/jim` directory and transfer it to `/home`.

## Objective
Practice creating compressed tar archives and moving files across system directories.

## Commands Used
```bash
# Navigate to home directory for clean execution
cd ~

# Create compressed archive
tar czvf jim.tar.gz /data/jim

# Move archive to /home using full path
sudo mv /data/jim/jim.tar.gz /home/

# Verify
ls -l /home/jim.tar.gz
```

## What the Commands Do
- `tar` is the archive utility.
- `c` creates a new archive.
- `z` compresses it using gzip.
- `v` prints verbose output showing files being archived.
- `f` specifies the output filename.
- `sudo mv` is required because `/home` is root-owned.
- `ls -l` confirms the archive exists at the destination.

## Troubleshooting
Running `tar` from inside `/data/jim` caused a `file changed as we read it` warning because the archive was being written into the same directory being archived. The fix is to run `tar` from outside the target directory.

## Verification
Confirmed `jim.tar.gz` was present in `/home` after the move.

## What I Learned
- How `z` flag applies gzip compression in `tar`.
- Why `/home` requires `sudo` to write into.
- Why running `tar` from inside the target directory causes a file change warning.
- How to use a full path in `mv` when the working directory is wrong.

## Personal Notes
This task reinforced that file extensions do not determine compression — the flags do. It also showed that working directory awareness matters when creating archives.
